    <title>Use Dioptas for Efficient 2D Powder Diffraction Data Reduction</title>
    <url>/Tools/Use%20Dioptas%20for%20Efficient%202D%20Powder%20Diffraction%20Data%20Reduction.html</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/cover.png" alt="2D Powder Diffraction" title="2D Powder Diffraction" width="50%">
<p>Dioptas is an awesome GUI program based on <em>Python</em>, designed for the fast data reduction of <em><strong>Powder X-ray Diffraction images</strong></em>. It provides the capability of <strong>calibrating</strong>, <strong>integrating</strong>, <strong>creating masks</strong>, showing multiple pattern overlays and display phases line positions.</p>
<span id="more"></span>
<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/Dioptas_Modules.png" alt="Dioptas_Modules" title="Dioptas_Modules" width="60%">
<h2 id="Program-dependencies">Program dependencies</h2>
<figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tbody><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">Python 3.9+</span><br><span class="line">pyFAI</span><br></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
<h2 id="Distribution">Distribution</h2>
<p><strong>Maintainer</strong></p>
<p>Clemens Prescher (<a href="mailto:clemens.prescher@gmail.com">clemens.prescher@gmail.com</a>)</p>
<figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tbody><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">https://github.com/Dioptas/Dioptas</span><br></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
<h2 id="Installation">Installation</h2>
<p><strong>Executables</strong></p>
<p>Binary programs for Windows, macOS, and Linux can be downloaded from the following link:</p>
<figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tbody><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">https://github.com/Dioptas/Dioptas/releases</span><br></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
<p><strong>pip</strong></p>
<p>Install the all the dependencies for <em>Dioptas</em> by pip package manager:</p>
<figure class="highlight shell"><table><tbody><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">pip install dioptas</span><br><span class="line"><span class="meta prompt_"># </span><span class="language-bash">run Dioptas</span></span><br><span class="line">dioptas</span><br></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
<p><strong>poetry</strong><br>
Use the poetry package manager to create a working environment by typing:</p>
<figure class="highlight shell"><table><tbody><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"><span class="meta prompt_"># </span><span class="language-bash">create new environment</span></span><br><span class="line">poetry install</span><br><span class="line"><span class="meta prompt_"># </span><span class="language-bash">Activate the environment</span></span><br><span class="line">poetry shell</span><br><span class="line"><span class="meta prompt_"># </span><span class="language-bash">run dioptas</span></span><br><span class="line">dioptas</span><br><span class="line"><span class="meta prompt_"># </span><span class="language-bash">run the dioptas without activating the environment</span></span><br><span class="line">poetry run dioptas</span><br></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
<h2 id="Procedure">Procedure</h2>
<pre class="mermaid">flowchart LR
    A(Load Image Data) --&gt;B(Calibration)
    B --&gt; C(Marks)
    C --&gt; D(Integration)
    D --&gt; E(Export Data)
    D --&gt;A</pre>
<h3 id="Overview">Overview</h3>
<p>Dioptas has three different modules which can all be accessed by the lab indicators on the <em><strong>left side</strong></em> of the user interface: <strong>Calibration</strong>, <strong>Mask</strong>, <strong>Integration</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Calibration Module</strong> This module is used to calibrate the detector geometry.</li>
<li><strong>Mask Module</strong> This module allows users to select regions that need to be excluded from the image integration.</li>
<li><strong>Integration Module</strong> This module displays the image and integrated pattern. It can overlay different patterns and show the line positions of phases.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id="Getting-Started">Getting Started</h3>
<p>Basic Mouse Operations</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Left Drag</strong> Zooms into the selected area.</li>
</ul>
<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/leftclick.gif" alt="Left Drag" title="Left Drag" width="60%">
<ul>
<li><strong>Right Click</strong> Zoom out.</li>
</ul>
<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/rightclick.gif" alt="Right Click" title="Right Click" width="60%">
<ul>
<li><strong>Right Double Click</strong> Completely Zoom out.</li>
</ul>
<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/rightdclick.gif" alt="Right Double Click" title="Right Double Click" width="60%">
<ul>
<li><strong>Mouse Wheel</strong> Zoom in and zoom out based on the current cursor position.</li>
</ul>
<img src="https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/Dioptas/mousewheel.gif" alt="Mouse Wheel" title="Mouse Wheel" width="60%">
